@course

id: book:thinking-fast-and-slow-hqkr
title: Thinking, Fast and Slow
author: Readlock
description: Why your mind runs on two different systems, and what happens when they disagree.
color: #0ea5e9
genres: psychology, decision-making
relevant_for: anyone, managers, investors

@segment
The Two Systems
TS

@package
The Anchor You Did Not See
Free

@text
There are numbers in our heads right now that we did not choose.
Prices we half-remember, distances we guessed once.
Most of the time they feel neutral.
But when we need to make a decision, they are the first numbers our minds reach for.
We do not notice it happen.

@text
A shopper sees a jacket marked "was 2,400, now 1,200."
She has never paid 2,400 for a jacket in her life.
She does not need a jacket this week.
But the 1,200 feels reasonable, and she leaves the store with the bag.
A week later she sees the same jacket elsewhere for 900.
She feels nothing about the 900.
It is just a number for a jacket she already owns.

@text
A judge is deciding how many months a shoplifter should spend in prison.
Before the ruling, a defense attorney mentions 5 months in an unrelated argument.
The judge ignores the comment. She is a professional.
Her ruling comes out closer to 5 months than it would have if the defense had said 12.
Not because she agreed with the defense.
The number was simply in the room.

@text
A buyer is negotiating the price of a house.
The seller names a number first, deliberately high.
The buyer knows the trick. He has read articles about it.
He offers a number lower than the seller's.
Still, his final offer lands closer to the seller's opening than he planned.
Knowing the trick did not protect him.
The number had already changed what felt reasonable.

@question
What connects the jacket, the judge, and the house negotiation?

answer: Each decision was pulled toward a number that was introduced first, even when the number had no real basis.
consequence: Exactly. The first number becomes the reference point. Every later number gets compared to it, not to reality.

answer: Each person was acting emotionally instead of rationally.
consequence: That is the usual explanation, but not quite right. The judge and the buyer were doing careful work. The bias happened inside their reasoning.

answer: Each person failed to do enough research before deciding.
consequence: The judge and the buyer had all the information they needed. More data would not have changed the pull of the first number.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: The first number in a decision sets a reference point that pulls every later number toward it. This is the anchoring effect.
hint: Notice what all three situations share: someone said a number first.

@text
Psychologists call this the <c:g>anchoring effect</c:g>.
The research behind it describes two modes of thought.
System 1 is fast, automatic, and runs on rough estimates.
System 2 is slow, deliberate, and wakes up only when asked.
Anchoring happens because System 1 grabs the first number as a starting point.
System 2 argues with it, but almost never throws it out.

@true_false
A person who knows about the anchoring effect can make decisions that are fully free of it.

true: True, awareness protects you.
consequence: Awareness helps, but less than you would expect. Experiments include judges and statisticians who anchor even when warned.

false: False, awareness reduces it but does not remove it.
consequence: That is the honest answer. Anchoring works below the level of deliberate thought. The best you can do is set your own number before seeing the anchor.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Knowing about a cognitive bias is not the same as being immune to it. The bias lives in System 1, and System 1 does not care what you have read.
hint: Has any unconscious habit ever stopped just because you learned about it.

@reflect
A number sitting in your head right now that you never chose yourself: last year's rent, or a salary you were once offered.
A recent purchase where a discount sticker made the price feel smaller than it was: a jacket, a subscription, a flight.
A moment when you made your own estimate before seeing the real price, and noticed the difference: buying coffee abroad.
